osteoarthritis.

308
00:16:41,217 --> 00:16:43,453
Is that why you haven't been
playing the drums?

309
00:16:43,453 --> 00:16:45,255
What?!

310
00:16:46,456 --> 00:16:47,924
Don't you fuck...

311
00:16:47,924 --> 00:16:49,725
How I restrain myself

312
00:16:49,725 --> 00:16:54,397
From throwing everything
at you, Jay, I don't know.

313
00:16:54,397 --> 00:16:58,068
There's nothing you can do
about it, is there?

314
00:16:58,068 --> 00:17:00,203
[Coughs]

315
00:17:01,371 --> 00:17:04,040
You're not gonna give up?

316
00:17:04,040 --> 00:17:08,278
Sometimes I feel like doing
just that.

317
00:17:19,089 --> 00:17:21,557
When you first met Jack Bruce,

318
00:17:21,557 --> 00:17:25,828
Was it as if you knew you had
met your musical counterpart?

319
00:17:25,828 --> 00:17:28,598
Early on, for sure, yeah.

320
00:17:28,598 --> 00:17:32,302
I mean, he's a fucking
brilliant player.

321
00:17:32,302 --> 00:17:34,504
There's no doubt about that.

322
00:17:34,504 --> 00:17:37,673
Ginger looked like
a complete and utter madman.

323
00:17:37,673 --> 00:17:40,110
He was the loudest drummer
I'd ever heard.

324
00:17:40,110 --> 00:17:43,980
And I wanted to play with him,
so I asked if I could sit in.

325
00:17:43,980 --> 00:17:48,918
Kept bugging us to sit in,
and he wouldn't fucking go away.

326
00:17:48,918 --> 00:17:50,753
So, of course,
they did the thing

327
00:17:50,753 --> 00:17:53,923
That jazz musicians always do,
which is to try and cut you.

328
00:17:53,923 --> 00:17:57,127
I think the first thing
they played was very, very fast.

329
00:17:57,127 --> 00:17:58,861
And he played it.

330
00:17:58,861 --> 00:18:00,863
[Laughs]

331
00:18:00,863 --> 00:18:03,133
Which is quite extraordinary.

332
00:18:03,133 --> 00:18:04,467
Jack got the gig

333
00:18:04,467 --> 00:18:07,670
With Alexis Korner's
Blues Incorporated,

334
00:18:07,670 --> 00:18:11,974
And none of them were
terribly happy with the drummer,

335
00:18:11,974 --> 00:18:13,676
Who was Charlie Watts.

336
00:18:13,676 --> 00:18:16,412
I actually don't know how long
Ginger was with the band.

337
00:18:16,412 --> 00:18:21,117
I know he took over for me,
on my recommendation.

338
00:18:21,117 --> 00:18:24,820
Charlie left the band
so that I could join.

339
00:18:24,820 --> 00:18:27,557
[Down-tempo jazz playing]

340
00:18:27,557 --> 00:18:30,593
Can you tell me the story
of Mick Jagger?

341
00:18:30,593 --> 00:18:32,295
[Mutters]

342
00:18:32,295 --> 00:18:36,466
"Can you tell me what it was
like meeting Mick Jagger?"

343
00:18:37,967 --> 00:18:43,439
This effeminate-looking kid
got up and sung one number.

344
00:18:43,439 --> 00:18:47,310
And I'm going, "Jack, who is
this stupid little cunt?"

345
00:18:47,310 --> 00:18:48,844
What's he doing here?"

346
00:18:48,844 --> 00:18:52,948
Jack and I used to put
some jazz things in,

347
00:18:52,948 --> 00:18:55,751
Completely throw him off.

348
00:18:55,751 --> 00:18:58,454
I mean, I was a heavy junkie
at the time,

349
00:18:58,454 --> 00:19:01,124
So I just terrified
the shit out of him.

350
00:19:01,124 --> 00:19:03,259
[Laughs]

351
00:19:03,259 --> 00:19:07,330
And then Alexis decided
to get Graham in the band.

352
00:19:07,330 --> 00:19:09,832
My first reaction to that was,
"Fucking no.

353
00:19:09,832 --> 00:19:13,136
Alexis, watch it, 'cause he'll
steal half the band,"

354
00:19:13,136 --> 00:19:14,637
Which is exactly what he did.

355
00:19:14,637 --> 00:19:17,607
Can you contextualize who we're
speaking about right now?

356
00:19:17,607 --> 00:19:20,343
Well, I've just said it,
for fuck's sake.

357
00:19:20,343 --> 00:19:21,811
You just said "Graham."
That's it.

358
00:19:21,811 --> 00:19:24,447
People who don't know
who Graham is.

359
00:19:26,549 --> 00:19:28,451
Graham Bond was a fat guy.

360
00:19:28,451 --> 00:19:30,153
[Harmonica playing]

361
00:19:30,153 --> 00:19:33,889
* Well, I was standing on
the corner, waiting to go home *

362
00:19:33,889 --> 00:19:37,160
* When I heard this sound
that made me want to go *

363
00:19:37,160 --> 00:19:41,264
* Well, it was coming from
a doss across the street *

364
00:19:41,264 --> 00:19:43,999
* It was kind of stompy,
with an R&B beat *

365
00:19:43,999 --> 00:19:45,168
* It went... *

366
00:19:45,168 --> 00:19:46,569
Harmonica!
Oh!

367
00:19:46,569 --> 00:19:49,805
Graham Bond Organization
was to musicians

368
00:19:49,805 --> 00:19:52,074
What The Beatles were
to the public.

369
00:19:52,074 --> 00:19:53,809
Brilliant.

370
00:19:53,809 --> 00:19:56,412
Jack Bruce, Ginger Baker,
Dick Heckstall-Smith,

371
00:19:56,412 --> 00:19:58,514
And Graham Bond were at the top.

372
00:19:58,514 --> 00:20:02,152
We were a band trying to be
like a band in Chicago.

373
00:20:02,152 --> 00:20:04,086
But they were something else,
