00:27:03,172 --> 00:27:06,475
That's where Jack's head is
writing.

508
00:27:06,475 --> 00:27:08,811
And I said,
"Man, that's terrible.

509
00:27:08,811 --> 00:27:12,147
Why don't you slow it down
and play it backwards?"

510
00:27:12,147 --> 00:27:15,317
Ba-da-da-ba, ba-ba...

511
00:27:16,185 --> 00:27:22,024
Another one is "White Room,"
the 5/4 bolero that makes it.

512
00:27:22,024 --> 00:27:26,228
Da, bum-bum-bum-bum,
bum-bum-bum, da...

513
00:27:26,228 --> 00:27:27,763
Wasn't written like that.

514
00:27:27,763 --> 00:27:29,965
Jack wrote it in 4/4.

515
00:27:29,965 --> 00:27:33,102
He now declares
"I wrote it in 5/4."

516
00:27:33,102 --> 00:27:34,036
I mean, hello?

517
00:27:34,036 --> 00:27:35,905
* In the white room *

518
00:27:35,905 --> 00:27:38,207
* With black curtains *

519
00:27:38,207 --> 00:27:41,310
* In the station *

520
00:27:42,077 --> 00:27:47,182
Today and for the last...
How long is it now?... 40 years,

521
00:27:47,182 --> 00:27:51,921
Pete Brown and Jack Bruce
have been earning

522
00:27:51,921 --> 00:27:55,357
A hell of a lot more money
from Cream

523
00:27:55,357 --> 00:28:00,062
Than Eric and I will ever earn,
to this day.

524
00:28:00,062 --> 00:28:02,231
The guy who gets the credit
for writing the song

525
00:28:02,231 --> 00:28:04,767
Is the guy who writes the lyric
gets half of it,

526
00:28:04,767 --> 00:28:06,869
And the guy who writes
the melody of the lyric

527
00:28:06,869 --> 00:28:08,170
Gets the other half.

528
00:28:08,170 --> 00:28:10,973
The drums are part
of the arrangement,

529
00:28:10,973 --> 00:28:13,175
And the arrangement
doesn't get royalties.

530
00:28:13,175 --> 00:28:14,176
Zip. Nada.

531
00:28:14,176 --> 00:28:16,245
Cream was my thing.

532
00:28:16,245 --> 00:28:19,281
And it did exactly
what I planned it to do.

533
00:28:19,281 --> 00:28:22,517
Only I'm the guy
who lost out on it.

534
00:28:22,517 --> 00:28:24,687
I'm fucking broke right now.

535
00:28:24,687 --> 00:28:28,658
* Run from themselves *

536
00:28:30,292 --> 00:28:32,895
[Crowd cheering]

537
00:28:39,034 --> 00:28:41,603
To Jack Bruce's counterpoint,
he gives rhythm,

538
00:28:41,603 --> 00:28:44,707
And to Eric Clapton's technical
virtuosity, he gives shape.

539
00:28:44,707 --> 00:28:47,409
On their first tour together,
he practiced so intensively

540
00:28:47,409 --> 00:28:49,879
That he left behind him
a trail of hotel bills

541
00:28:49,879 --> 00:28:51,246
For broken furniture.

542
00:28:51,246 --> 00:28:53,415
We asked him
if he still practiced as much.

543
00:28:53,415 --> 00:28:56,618
No.
I don't practice at all.

544
00:28:56,618 --> 00:28:58,120
Not at all?

545
00:28:58,120 --> 00:28:59,955
I used to, but I don't anymore.

546
00:28:59,955 --> 00:29:02,324
I just used to play solos.

547
00:29:02,324 --> 00:29:06,829
Just used to sit on the drum kit
and play it all day.

548
00:29:06,829 --> 00:29:08,030
Can you show us some?

549
00:29:08,030 --> 00:29:10,332
- You want me to play?
- Please.

550
00:29:10,332 --> 00:29:13,402
[Chuckles]
At this time of the day.

551
00:29:26,949 --> 00:29:31,887
Independence... the ability
to play a different thing

552
00:29:31,887 --> 00:29:34,023
With all four limbs,

553
00:29:34,023 --> 00:29:37,292
Which is how I play things
that sound incredibly fast

554
00:29:37,292 --> 00:29:40,562
When I'm not actually moving
anything very fast.

555
00:29:40,562 --> 00:29:43,699
Because all four beats are
landing in a different place,

556
00:29:43,699 --> 00:29:46,601
So what comes out
is four times as fast.

557
00:29:46,601 --> 00:29:48,003
[Laughs]

558
00:29:48,003 --> 00:29:51,640
But it's not how fast you play.

559
00:29:51,640 --> 00:29:53,776
It's what you say.

560
00:29:53,776 --> 00:29:55,978
[Drum solo]

561
00:30:01,350 --> 00:30:03,986
Ginger Baker's
most notable achievement

562
00:30:03,986 --> 00:30:06,789
That should be recognized
is the first rock drum solo.

563
00:30:06,789 --> 00:30:08,758
And me as a 15-year-old kid
at the time

564
00:30:08,758 --> 00:30:11,593
Was like, "Yeah, yeah, that's
the rock drummer I want to be."

565
00:30:11,593 --> 00:30:12,795
I must have been 16.

566
00:30:12,795 --> 00:30:14,396
I was exactly the sweet spot

567
00:30:14,396 --> 00:30:17,733
Where my brain clicked on
and said, "What's it all about?"

568
00:30:17,733 --> 00:30:18,968
It was Ginger's drums.

569
00:30:18,968 --> 00:30:21,003
I'm here today
because of Ginger,

570
00:30:21,003 --> 00:30:23,839
Because he was
the absolute inspiration

571
00:30:23,839 --> 00:30:26,641
For me being in a band,
playing the drums.

572
00:30:26,641 --> 00:30:30,412
I absolutely thought, "You know,
that's what I'd like to be."

573
00:30:34,416 --> 00:30:36,752
[Music continues]

574
00:30:39,688 --> 00:30:41,123
It became Ginger's thing.

575
00:30:41,123 --> 00:30:43,458
He'd do these very long
drum solos.

576
00:30:43,458 --> 00:30:45,961
You either liked them
or you didn't like them.

577
00:30:45,961 --> 00:30:49,598
I liked them because I could go
off and have a smoke, you know?

578
00:30:49,598 --> 00:30:51,533
Cream... How popular were they?

579
00:30:51,533 --> 00:30:52,835
Oh, huge, huge.

580
00:30:52,835 --> 00:30:54,336
How huge is "huge"?

581
00:30:54,336 --> 00:30:57,006
Well, they did three nights
in Madison Square Garden.

582
00:30:57,006 --> 00:31:00,109
They could have done two weeks
and sold out every night.

583
00:31:00,109 --> 00:31:02,444
When a promoter hired
The Cream,

584
00:31:02,444 --> 00:31:05,881
Ginger wanted a case of beer
and two black hookers

585
00:31:05,881 --> 00:31:08,517
And a white limo
or he wouldn't play.

586
00:31:08,517 --> 00:31:09,751
I've been in hotel rooms,

587
00:31:09,751 --> 00:31:11,420
And there's been a knock on
the door.

588
00:31:11,420 --> 00:31:12,754
I've opened the door,

589
00:31:12,754 --> 00:31:15,290
And there's been three groupies
all standing there.

590
00:31:15,290 --> 00:31:17,626
Just queues of chicks waiting.
[Laughs]

591
00:31:17,626 --> 00:31:20,462
One would knock on the door
and climb into bed.

592
00:31:20,462 --> 00:31:22,998
We used to call them
"star fuckers."

593
00:31:22,998 --> 00:31:24,666
You know, they'd come
and say like,

594
00:31:24,666 --> 00:31:27,369
"I'd like to give you a blowjob
and see you come."

595
00:31:27,369 --> 00:31:31,406
They all wanted to fuck Cream,
you know?

596
00:31:31,406 --> 00:31:35,010
It was quite a rapid rise
to fame.

597
00:31:35,010 --> 00:31:38,547
I don't know whether it was
too fast for Ginger.

598
00:31:38,547 --> 00:31:39,982
I didn't really care.

599
00:31:39,982 --> 00:31:43,752
We'd lived in a succession
of not very nice places.

600
00:31:43,752 --> 00:31:45,087
And then for once, we thought,

601
00:31:45,087 --> 00:31:48,457
"Oh, we can actually buy
a house of our own."

602
00:31:48,457 --> 00:31:51,894
The family at home
was something totally separate

603
00:31:51,894 --> 00:31:54,229
From being on tour.

604
00:31:54,229 --> 00:31:57,232
His dad died when he was 4
or something like that.

605
00:31:57,232 --> 00:32:01,736
So he didn't really have
someone, a role-model father.

606
00:32:01,736 --> 00:32:07,176
He communicates more through his
drums than through his words.

607
00:32:07,176 --> 00:32:11,113
I told my wife
long before we were married,

608
00:32:11,113 --> 00:32:15,317
"If you get me to choose
between the drums and you,

609
00:32:15,317 --> 00:32:17,419
I'm gonna choose the drums."

610
00:32:17,419 --> 00:32:18,954
[Chuckles]

611
00:32:18,954 --> 00:32:21,090
We had no other interest.

612
00:32:21,090 --> 00:32:23,192
There was nothing else going on.

613
00:32:23,192 --> 00:32:24,860
There was no family.

614
00:32:24,860 --> 00:32:27,396
There was no desires
for success.

615
00:32:27,396 --> 00:32:30,265
There was no commerciality
involved.

616
00:32:30,265 --> 00:32:31,901
There was no responsibility

617
00:32:31,901 --> 00:32:36,071
Other than to that unique moment
in time when we were together.

618
00:32:36,071 --> 00:32:38,540
And for a short,
sweet period of time,

619
00:32:38,540 --> 00:32:42,611
It was unfettered and extreme
and beautiful.

620
00:32:42,611 --> 00:32:43,879
They were like Vikings.

621
00:32:43,879 --> 00:32:45,547
You know, they just came
on our shore

622
00:32:45,547 --> 00:32:48,450
And just took the women
and the children,

623
00:32:48,450 --> 00:32:51,253
It was scorched earth.
There was no question about it.

624
00:32:51,253 --> 00:32:53,288
They were here to take heads.

625
00:32:53,288 --> 00:32:57,592
We went there to show the Yanks
how to play.

626
00:32:57,592 --> 00:32:59,528
I saw them when they first came
to San Francisco.

627
00:32:59,528 --> 00:33:03,698
They looked and sounded
like giants.

628
00:33:03,698 --> 00:33:08,170
They took off and started
playing supersonic music.

629
00:33:08,170 --> 00:33:12,774
And supersonic music is when
the Holy Ghost takes over

630
00:33:12,774 --> 00:33:15,844
And you're playing something
that, when you hear it back,

631
00:33:15,844 --> 00:33:17,846
You have no idea
what the hell you did.

632
00:33:17,846 --> 00:33:20,649
[Up-tempo rock music playing]

633
00:33:56,418 --> 00:34:00,589
There was something about that
little chemistry that we had,

634
00:34:00,589 --> 00:34:02,257
Ginger and me and Eric.

635
00:34:02,257 --> 00:34:04,759
It'll never be repeated
by anybody else.

636
00:34:04,759 --> 00:34:08,763
Cream... They were together
shorter than our last tour.

637
00:34:08,763 --> 00:34:12,201
You know, we've been on the road
for two years and two months.

638
00:34:12,201 --> 00:34:15,104
That's two months longer
than their entire life-span.

639
00:34:15,104 --> 00:34:17,039
Sam Kinison would say,
"I've had parties

640
00:34:17,039 --> 00:34:18,773
That lasted
more than two years."

641
00:34:18,773 --> 00:34:23,578
* We... *

642
00:34:23,578 --> 00:34:25,314
[Crowd cheering]

643
00:34:25,314 --> 00:34:30,419
Cream only lasted as long as it
did because it was so popular.

644
00:34:30,419 --> 00:34:35,124
I just couldn't handle
working with Jack anymore.

645
00:34:35,124 --> 00:34:36,958
Whatever energy was happening

646
00:34:36,958 --> 00:34:40,062
Between Jack Bruce
and Ginger Baker

647
00:34:40,062 --> 00:34:42,897
Also mounted Eric

648
00:34:42,897 --> 00:34:47,136
To play beyond what he was
playing with John Mayall

649
00:34:47,136 --> 00:34:49,138
Or later on, all the other bands
that he played.

650
00:34:49,138 --> 00:34:51,440
They focused on one another
all the time

651
00:34:51,440 --> 00:34:53,808
For their aggression
and their frustrations,

652
00:34:53,808 --> 00:34:55,210
And it wore me out.

653
00:34:55,210 --> 00:34:57,946
I remember Eric breaking down
in tears once.

654
00:34:57,946 --> 00:35:01,483
[Laughs]
That was not very good.

655
00:35:01,483 --> 00:35:02,617
Sorry, Eric.

656
00:35:02,617 --> 00:35:04,553
From time to time,
I would break down

657
00:35:04,553 --> 00:35:06,588
And just go,
"I can't stand this anymore."

658
00:35:06,588 --> 00:35:08,690
'Cause I was really
on the sidelines,

659
00:35:08,690 --> 00:35:11,026
And I knew I couldn't
affect anything,

660
00:35:11,026 --> 00:35:13,628
Because I didn't have
the understanding

661
00:35:13,628 --> 00:35:16,698
Or the power to be able to do
anything about it.

662
00:35:16,698 --> 00:35:18,500
You'd just run, really.

663
00:35:18,500 --> 00:35:21,570
And, you know, when Cream,
I thought, had run its course,

664
00:35:21,570 --> 00:35:25,207
I was quite keen to get out of
there and have a break, really.

665
00:35:29,311 --> 00:35:31,580
A banger...
You know, a firework,

666
00:35:31,580 --> 00:35:33,515
Whatever you call them...
Cracker or whatever...

667
00:35:33,515 --> 00:35:35,550
They only last a second,
don't they,

668
00:35:35,550 --> 00:35:37,886
And they fizzle up
and burn up and that's it.

669
00:35:37,886 --> 00:35:40,789
It's all dead and gone.
And the band was like that.

670
00:35:40,789 --> 00:35:44,126
They were never, ever going to
be a long-lasting band.

671
00:35:44,126 --> 00:35:50,031
* We're going wrong *

672
00:35:50,031 --> 00:35:51,800
[Music ends]

673
00:36:03,112 --> 00:36:05,414
Hello, Bonnie.

674
00:36:13,555 --> 00:36:20,629
Mimosa, don't be scared
of the camera.

675
00:36:22,764 --> 00:36:27,302
You're a soldier boy,
aren't you?

676
00:36:27,302 --> 00:36:30,772
Big old, tough soldier boy.

677
00:36:35,910 --> 00:36:39,548
Eric and I decided
that we wanted to get together

678
00:36:39,548 --> 00:36:41,950
With this project
with Blind Faith.

679
00:36:42,551 --> 00:36:46,388
And...
[Tires screech]

680
00:36:47,256 --> 00:36:49,258
Ginger showed up.

681
00:36:49,258 --> 00:36:51,260
[Engine revs]

682
00:36:51,260 --> 00:36:54,663
I just hit it off musically
with Stevie

683
00:36:54,663 --> 00:36:58,133
In the same way
as I had hit off with Eric.

684
00:36:58,133 --> 00:37:00,802
Stevie had time.

685
00:37:00,802 --> 00:37:04,939
I actually didn't realize
until quite a bit later

686
00:37:04,939 --> 00:37:07,242
That Eric was so horrified

687
00:37:07,242 --> 00:37:11,213
That he was hooking up
with Ginger again.

688
00:37:11,213 --> 00:37:14,149
The last person
that Eric wanted on drums

689
00:37:14,149 --> 00:37:16,618
With his new venture was Ginger.

690
00:37:16,618 --> 00:37:21,022
I believe he turned up
at a rehearsal and said, "Right."

691
00:37:21,022 --> 00:37:23,024
Where do we start?"

692
00:37:23,024 --> 00:37:25,594
["Had To Cry Today" plays]

693
00:37:28,096 --> 00:37:30,699
* It's already written *

694
00:37:30,699 --> 00:37:35,837
* That today will be one
to remember *

695
00:37:39,274 --> 00:37:42,511
* The feeling's the same *

696
00:37:42,511 --> 00:37:47,449
* As being outside of the law *

697
00:37:52,287 --> 00:37:56,691
* Had to cry today *

698
00:38:02,030 --> 00:38:06,835
* Saw your sign,
and I missed you then *

699
00:38:08,337 --> 00:38:10,972
We were called a supergroup
from day one.

700
00:38:10,972 --> 00:38:12,607
We hit the road too early.

701
00:38:12,607 --> 00:38:15,377
And, you know,
it overpowered us.

702
00:38:16,645 --> 00:38:21,250
I think Ginger was as happy
as a pig in shit in Blind Faith.

703
00:38:21,250 --> 00:38:24,786
You know, there was no one...
There was Rick Grech...

704
00:38:24,786 --> 00:38:28,690
Great player, you know,
but no Jack Bruce.

705
00:38:28,690 --> 00:38:31,360
And Ginger could fucking do
what he wants.

706
00:38:31,360 --> 00:38:42,203
* Do what you like *

707
00:38:42,203 --> 00:38:47,709
I was driving a Shelby Cobra
up the coast to Los Angeles

708
00:38:47,709 --> 00:38:51,212
With three gorgeous chicks
in the car.

709
00:38:51,212 --> 00:38:54,549
And the radio station
stopped the music

710
00:38:54,549 --> 00:38:59,721
With the news that Ginger Baker,
Blind Faith drummer,

711
00:38:59,721 --> 00:39:02,624
Had just been found dead
in his hotel room

712
00:39:02,624 --> 00:39:04,793
From a heroin overdose.

713
00:39:04,793 --> 00:39:07,195
[Laughs]

714
00:39:07,195 --> 00:39:10,399
And I went "Fucking hell.
I must be in heaven," you know?

715
00:39:10,399 --> 00:39:13,335
I'm driving this supercar
with three super chicks.

716
00:39:13,335 --> 00:39:14,669
[Laughs]

717
00:39:14,669 --> 00:39:17,171
["Do What You Like" plays]

718
00:39:17,171 --> 00:39:20,208
There was huge amounts
of drugs,

719
00:39:20,208 --> 00:39:25,580
Which at the time, I must admit,
I didn't really know about,

720
00:39:25,580 --> 00:39:28,417
Because I was probably smoking
so much weed,

721
00:39:28,417 --> 00:39:30,719
I didn't really know
what was going on anyway.

722
00:39:30,719 --> 00:39:34,689
Every time
we got to Los Angeles,

723
00:39:34,689 --> 00:39:36,791
The drugs would appear,

724
00:39:36,791 --> 00:39:41,530
So I decided to go to Hawaii
after the tour

725
00:39:41,530 --> 00:39:44,198
To try and get straight.

726
00:39:44,198 --> 00:39:47,235
So Liz come out with the kids.

727
00:39:47,235 --> 00:39:50,572
Considering all the places
we've left him before,

728
00:39:50,572 --> 00:39:53,375
I have to say it was marvelous.

729
00:39:53,375 --> 00:39:55,744
["Can't Find My Way Home"
plays]

730
00:39:55,744 --> 00:40:01,650
* You are the reason
I've been waiting so long *

731
00:40:01,650 --> 00:40:06,187
* Somebody holds the key *

732
00:40:06,187 --> 00:40:08,923
* Well, I'm near the end *

733
00:40:08,923 --> 00:40:13,895
* And I just ain't got
the time *

734
00:40:15,263 --> 00:40:17,332
* And I'm wasted *

735
00:40:17,332 --> 00:40:22,737
* And I can't find my way home *

736
00:40:22,737 --> 00:40:25,740
Only at that time,
there was more heroin on Hawaii

737
00:40:25,740 --> 00:40:28,410
Than there was in Los Angeles.

738
00:40:28,410 --> 00:40:32,180
It wasn't a good place to be
to get straight.

739
00:40:32,180 --> 00:40:34,816
So we decided to go to Jamaica.

740
00:40:34,816 --> 00:40:37,752
That's when I flew my car out.

741
00:40:37,752 --> 00:40:42,491
That is wild, to fly your car
over to Jamaica.

742
00:40:42,491 --> 00:40:44,793
That's crazy.

743
00:40:44,793 --> 00:40:49,498
You get to feel that the money
is inexhaustible,

744
00:40:49,498 --> 00:40:51,299
Which, of course, it isn't.

745
00:40:51,299 --> 00:40:55,570
It was like nearly three months
after the last gig

746
00:40:55,570 --> 00:40:57,972
That I came back to London.

747
00:40:57,972 --> 00:41:02,644
I'd brought back quite a lot
of dope in some masks and stuff.

748
00:41:02,644 --> 00:41:04,913
And so I went to see Stevie

749
00:41:04,913 --> 00:41:08,583
With a bag of grass
as a little present.

750
00:41:08,583 --> 00:41:12,053
And he told me that Eric
had gone off

751
00:41:12,053 --> 00:41:14,456
With Delaney and Bonnie

752
00:41:14,456 --> 00:41:17,125
And he was getting Traffic
back together.

753
00:41:17,125 --> 00:41:20,795
I take full responsibility
for having, you know,

754
00:41:20,795 --> 00:41:22,997
Strong interests
in going somewhere else.

755
00:41:22,997 --> 00:41:27,602
But they wouldn't have been
quite so strong

756
00:41:27,602 --> 00:41:30,539
If the core of the band
had been better.

757
00:41:30,539 --> 00:41:34,609
Were you hurt at all that Eric
had left without telling you?

758
00:41:34,609 --> 00:41:37,679
No.
You could see it coming.

759
00:41:37,679 --> 00:41:40,148
Something to do with me
getting so fucked up

760
00:41:40,148 --> 00:41:42,617
On the end of the tour.

761
00:41:42,617 --> 00:41:46,688
He's the best friend I've got
on this planet

762
00:41:46,688 --> 00:41:50,224
And always will be, okay?

763
00:41:50,224 --> 00:41:54,563
Whether it be polo
or the drums or drugs,

764
00:41:54,563 --> 00:41:57,799
Ginger seems to always go
full force

765
00:41:57,799 --> 00:41:59,734
Into whatever he's doing.

766
00:41:59,734 --> 00:42:02,737
Compulsion.
We're talking about compulsion.

767
00:42:02,737 --> 00:42:07,976
You know, what's the payoff
in being compulsive?

768
00:42:07,976 --> 00:42:12,614
You know, for Ginger, I'm not
gonna be his doctor in this

769
00:42:12,614 --> 00:42:15,717
Or psychologist
or make a diagnosis.

770
00:42:15,717 --> 00:42:18,252
I can't make a diagnosis
of Ginger.

771
00:42:18,252 --> 00:42:21,189
When I was driving in today,

772
00:42:21,189 --> 00:42:24,158
I thought, "Well, do I know
Ginger well?"

773
00:42:24,158 --> 00:42:25,627
Do I?"

774
00:42:25,627 --> 00:42:29,731
I've been with him
in fairly rarefied situations,

775
00:42:29,731 --> 00:42:32,333
Which allowed me to see
certain sides of him.

776
00:42:32,333 --> 00:42:35,336
I probably haven't seen him
like you've seen him,

777
00:42:35,336 --> 00:42:38,473
Because I didn't take
the effort, the time,

778
00:42:38,473 --> 00:42:42,276
The risk to step into his life
and become a part of it

779
00:42:42,276 --> 00:42:44,078
For any length of time.

780
00:42:44,078 --> 00:42:46,014
You know,
I've always pulled back

781
00:42:46,014 --> 00:42:49,083
When it started to get scary
or threatening

782
00:42:49,083 --> 00:42:51,620
Or just difficult.

783
00:42:52,987 --> 00:42:55,857
You guys want to wait a minute?
'Cause I'm about to cry.

784
00:42:55,857 --> 00:42:56,725
Why?

785
00:42:56,725 --> 00:42:58,960
'Cause, I mean...

786
00:42:58,960 --> 00:43:01,262
[Voice breaking]
I might cry.

787
00:43:01,262 --> 00:43:02,931
Why? Because Ginger is...

788
00:43:02,931 --> 00:43:05,834
He's all by himself, all alone,
in the woods or something.

789
00:43:05,834 --> 00:43:07,468
Well, he's got a wife.
He's got...

790
00:43:07,468 --> 00:43:08,970
Oh!
Well, then I won't.

791
00:43:08,970 --> 00:43:10,271
[Laughter]

792
00:43:10,271 --> 00:43:14,108
You guys are trying to live
a pretty quiet life here.

793
00:43:14,108 --> 00:43:17,078
As quiet as possible.

794
00:43:21,182 --> 00:43:23,985
Lisa's a little angel.

795
00:43:23,985 --> 00:43:26,120
Hello, Lisa.

796
00:43:27,922 --> 00:43:30,024
I'm extremely fond of her.

797
00:43:30,024 --> 00:43:32,260
I think of her
like she's my own.

798
00:43:32,260 --> 00:43:34,395
I wasn't studying yesterday.

799
00:43:34,395 --> 00:43:35,664
[Both laugh]

800
00:43:35,664 --> 00:43:38,767
She's a great little kid.

801
00:43:38,767 --> 00:43:42,470
It's really nice
to have a family again.

802
00:43:42,470 --> 00:43:44,005
[Laughter]

803
00:43:44,005 --> 00:43:49,811
If that falls apart,
I really don't know what to do.

804
00:43:49,811 --> 00:43:52,647
So Ginger is a good stepfather?

805
00:43:56,350 --> 00:43:58,286
Stepfather.

806
00:43:59,654 --> 00:44:01,856
Yeah.

807
00:44:01,856 --> 00:44:06,828
Do you find yourself
to be a tragic hero?

808
00:44:06,828 --> 00:44:08,763
Go on with the interview.

809
00:44:08,763 --> 00:44:12,066
Stop trying to be
an intellectual dickhead.

810
00:44:12,066 --> 00:44:14,068
["Toady" plays]

811
00:44:14,068 --> 00:44:15,269
[Drum solo]

812
00:44:41,830 --> 00:44:43,932
[Music continues]

813
00:44:49,704 --> 00:44:52,340
* Tell me *

814
00:44:52,340 --> 00:44:55,576
* Tell me, Toady *

815
00:44:55,576 --> 00:44:57,111
Ginger's not just a player.

816
00:44:57,111 --> 00:44:59,347
He's also a bandleader
and arranger.

817
00:44:59,347 --> 00:45:02,651
We were all brought up
on the big-band era, you know?

818
00:45:02,651 --> 00:45:05,386
And that's what Air force
was like.

819
00:45:05,386 --> 00:45:07,822
* Tell me *

820
00:45:07,822 --> 00:45:10,859
* Tell me, Toady *

821
00:45:10,859 --> 00:45:14,495
I made a stupid decision
of saying, "Okay."

822
00:45:14,495 --> 00:45:18,032
"Well, I've made my money
with Cream and Blind Faith,

823
00:45:18,032 --> 00:45:21,402
So I will pay the band
all the money."

824
00:45:21,402 --> 00:45:23,838
Just ridiculously expensive...
Hotel bills,

825
00:45:23,838 --> 00:45:25,974
The transportation, the wages.

826
00:45:25,974 --> 00:45:29,343
The name came from
the air force section

827
00:45:29,343 --> 00:45:33,581
Of the Duke Ellington Band,
which was the junkie section.

828
00:45:33,581 --> 00:45:35,249
It really was an air force.

829
00:45:35,249 --> 00:45:38,152
I think somebody said that they
were flying at 30,000 feet,

830
00:45:38,152 --> 00:45:39,688
I think it was.
[Laughs]

831
00:45:39,688 --> 00:45:41,322
It was a very high band.

832
00:45:41,322 --> 00:45:44,192
[Music continues]

833
00:45:44,192 --> 00:45:48,062
Now they're saying Air force
was some kind of a fusion band.

834
00:45:48,062 --> 00:45:50,398
I don't know
what the fuck that is.

835
00:45:50,398 --> 00:45:55,704
You can't put music in boxes,
especially my music.

836
00:45:55,704 --> 00:45:58,039
[Music ends]

837
00:46:03,812 --> 00:46:05,847
It was really exciting.

838
00:46:05,847 --> 00:46:07,548
I thought it was gonna last
forever.

839
00:46:07,548 --> 00:46:12,186
But, you know, Ginger's bands
have tended to be like that.

840
00:46:12,186 --> 00:46:13,587
Didn't they?

841
00:46:13,587 --> 00:46:15,023
Like what?

842
00:46:15,023 --> 00:46:16,891
You hear them,
you think, "This is fabulous."

843
00:46:16,891 --> 00:46:18,326
It's gonna go on forever."

844
00:46:18,326 --> 00:46:19,828
And it lasts a week.

845
00:46:19,828 --> 00:46:22,831
Maybe that's just part
of being him, you know?

846
00:46:22,831 --> 00:46:24,565
I don't know.

847
00:46:24,565 --> 00:46:28,169
Because of his fame from Cream
and Blind Faith,

848
00:46:28,169 --> 00:46:29,904
You know, he was considered

849
00:46:29,904 --> 00:46:31,973
The great rock drummer
of his generation.

850
00:46:31,973 --> 00:46:34,809
But as Ginger will tell you,
he was a jazz drummer.

851
00:46:34,809 --> 00:46:38,579
The general public
are so fucking dumb.

852
00:46:38,579 --> 00:46:44,085
That, you know, like, that
anybody could think of Bonham

853
00:46:44,085 --> 00:46:49,057
Was anywhere near
this kind of drummer I am,

854
00:46:49,057 --> 00:46:51,826
It's just extraordinary.

855
00:46:51,826 --> 00:46:54,328
Bonham had technique,

856
00:46:54,328 --> 00:46:58,099
But he couldn't swing
a fucking sack of shit.

857
00:46:58,099 --> 00:47:00,769
Or Moonie, for that matter.

858
00:47:00,769 --> 00:47:05,273
I mean, if they were still alive
today, ask them.

859
00:47:05,273 --> 00:47:07,441
[Laughs]

860
00:47:07,441 --> 00:47:08,777
When they think of Ginger,

861
00:47:08,777 --> 00:47:10,544
They think of Keith Moon
and Bonham.

862
00:47:10,544 --> 00:47:13,147
No, no, no, no.

863
00:47:13,147 --> 00:47:15,750
Ginger was nothing like
those players.

864
00:47:15,750 --> 00:47:18,352
His musical capabilities
are full-spectrum.

865
00:47:18,352 --> 00:47:20,521
He can write
and compose and arrange,

866
00:47:20,521 --> 00:47:23,224
And he has an ear,
and he is harmonic.

867
00:47:23,224 --> 00:47:25,159
He's a fully formed musician.

868
00:47:25,159 --> 00:47:27,762
He wanted to be respected
by the jazz drummers,

869
00:47:27,762 --> 00:47:29,630
So Ginger did these drum battles

870
00:47:29,630 --> 00:47:32,767
With the guys he looked up to,
thought were the great drummers.

871
00:47:32,767 --> 00:47:34,969
[Drum solo]

872
00:47:37,906 --> 00:47:39,774
[Whistling]

873
00:47:44,045 --> 00:47:46,114
[Drumming continues]

874
00:48:13,341 --> 00:48:15,209
[Crowd cheering]

875
00:48:21,883 --> 00:48:24,085
[Cheers and applause]

876
00:48:32,693 --> 00:48:34,062
[Applause]

877
00:48:34,062 --> 00:48:36,130
What always happens
is you end up,

878
00:48:36,130 --> 00:48:37,999
If you're playing
with a good guy,

879
00:48:37,999 --> 00:48:39,834
You end up playing together.

880
00:49:06,627 --> 00:49:08,897
[Drumming continues]

881
00:49:10,164 --> 00:49:13,067
[Cheers and applause]

882
00:49:14,969 --> 00:49:17,171
By him taking
all these guys on...

883
00:49:17,171 --> 00:49:20,141
And nobody else really did
in the "rock world"...

884
00:49:20,141 --> 00:49:24,145
He was considered to be
in that elite echelon

885
00:49:24,145 --> 00:49:26,480
Of great jazz drummers,
which, ultimately,

886
00:49:26,480 --> 00:49:28,549
That's what he considered
himself to be...

887
00:49:28,549 --> 00:49:31,219
The great jazz drummer
of his generation.

888
00:49:31,219 --> 00:49:34,155
[British accent]
Not a fucking rock drummer.

889
00:49:34,155 --> 00:49:37,358
So, here you are,
at the height of your career.

890
00:49:37,358 --> 00:49:39,827
You've battled
all the greatest drummers.

891
00:49:39,827 --> 00:49:41,495
You've become a bandleader.

892
00:49:41,495 --> 00:49:44,432
[Laughing]
And you decide to go to Africa.

893
00:49:44,432 --> 00:49:46,200
Oh, God.

894
00:49:46,700 --> 00:49:55,709
Way back, when Phil turned me on
to all the African drummers,

895
00:49:55,709 --> 00:50:04,318
It was obviously very high on my
priorities to go to Africa.

896
00:50:05,519 --> 00:50:08,756
Ginger says, "How do you feel
about filming me"

897
00:50:08,756 --> 00:50:09,991
Going across the Sahara?"

898
00:50:09,991 --> 00:50:11,825
And I said,
"How are you proposing

899
00:50:11,825 --> 00:50:13,461
To go across the Sahara,
Ginger?"

900
00:50:13,461 --> 00:50:15,063
And he said, "I'm gonna drive."

901
00:50:15,063 --> 00:50:18,132
* Ah-ah-ah-ah *

902
00:50:18,132 --> 00:50:21,135
* Ah-ah-ah *

903
00:50:21,135 --> 00:50:24,605
* Ah-ah-ah-ah *

904
00:50:24,605 --> 00:50:25,873
* Ah-ah-ah *

905
00:50:25,873 --> 00:50:28,376
[Man singing
in native language]

906
00:50:30,678 --> 00:50:34,082
* Ah-ah-ah *

907
00:50:34,082 --> 00:50:36,951
* Ah-ah-ah *

908
00:50:36,951 --> 00:50:39,920
* Ah-ah-ah *

909
00:50:39,920 --> 00:50:42,390
[Singing continues]

910
00:50:48,762 --> 00:50:52,533
There was that questing spirit
of a true artist there.

911
00:50:52,533 --> 00:50:55,369
It was news
that Ginger dropped out,

912
00:50:55,369 --> 00:50:57,571
Or he went following the groove.

913
00:50:57,571 --> 00:50:59,340
[Music continues]

914
00:51:01,942 --> 00:51:04,178
From Africa.

915
00:51:04,178 --> 00:51:06,380
[Drums playing]

916
00:51:08,449 --> 00:51:12,286
He predates everybody else
who later on said,

917
00:51:12,286 --> 00:51:14,788
"We discovered
the sounds of Africa."

918
00:51:14,788 --> 00:51:18,792
The only person that made me
cry before playing was Phil,

919
00:51:18,792 --> 00:51:20,528
And these guys had me crying,

920
00:51:20,528 --> 00:51:24,865
Because the time things they
were doing were just so subtle.

921
00:51:24,865 --> 00:51:27,535
This is why I went to Africa.

922
00:51:31,739 --> 00:51:34,508
When I arrived in Nigeria,

923
00:51:34,508 --> 00:51:39,113
I went straight
to the Afro Spot.

924
00:51:39,113 --> 00:51:41,849
And there was Fela
playing onstage.

925
00:51:41,849 --> 00:51:47,421
And it was just like, "Wow, man.
This is cool."

926
00:51:47,421 --> 00:51:49,623
[Up-tempo music playing]

927
00:51:52,493 --> 00:51:58,232
It was unlike anything
anybody else was playing.

928
00:51:58,232 --> 00:52:00,701
Fela was like,
"That's Ginger Baker!

929
00:52:00,701 --> 00:52:03,037
That's Ginger Baker!"

930
00:52:05,039 --> 00:52:06,574
Who is Fela?

931
00:52:06,574 --> 00:52:09,943
Some say he's the greatest
musician in Africa,

932
00:52:09,943 --> 00:52:13,681
Others that he's a prophet,
still others that he's a rebel,

933
00:52:13,681 --> 00:52:14,915
A revolutionary tribune.

934
00:52:14,915 --> 00:52:18,219
Fela was one of the most
important, influential,

935
00:52:18,219 --> 00:52:21,222
And courageous musicians
of the 20th century.

936
00:52:21,222 --> 00:52:23,257
[Music continues]

937
00:52:23,257 --> 00:52:25,326
Ginger got the opportunity

938
00:52:25,326 --> 00:52:27,961
To sit in the drum chair
for a while

939
00:52:27,961 --> 00:52:29,197
Of one of the greatest bands

940
00:52:29,197 --> 00:52:31,299
Ever to play
African popular music.

941
00:52:34,602 --> 00:52:37,338
[Singing in native language]

942
00:52:43,411 --> 00:52:46,947
Ginger was very close
to everybody...

943
00:52:46,947 --> 00:52:49,950
The girls, my father, the band.

944
00:52:49,950 --> 00:52:52,686
It was a color-blind situation.

945
00:52:52,686 --> 00:52:56,424
They smoked together, they drank
together, had women together.

946
00:52:56,424 --> 00:52:58,426
They played together...
Everything together.

947
00:52:58,426 --> 00:53:00,628
[Music continues]

948
00:53:27,855 --> 00:53:31,459
The first... or only Western
musician to go out there

949
00:53:31,459 --> 00:53:33,794
And immerse himself
and live in it,

950
00:53:33,794 --> 00:53:37,198
In the squalor of it,
was Ginger.

951
00:53:42,370 --> 00:53:45,339
And this studio became
the first 16-track studio

952
00:53:45,339 --> 00:53:48,008
We've got in our country.

953
00:53:48,008 --> 00:53:49,943
Fela stopped using EMI

954
00:53:49,943 --> 00:53:53,814
And started to use
Ginger Baker's studio.

955
00:53:53,814 --> 00:53:58,486
Now, who leaves England
to go and record in Lagos?

956
00:53:58,486 --> 00:54:02,723
Africa at that time in Nigeria
was an absolute hotbed

957
00:54:02,723 --> 00:54:09,430
Of revolution, of death,
of unaccountable violence.

958
00:54:10,298 --> 00:54:14,435
It was a great place to be
in those days.

959
00:54:14,435 --> 00:54:17,338
[Mid-tempo rock music plays]

960
00:54:18,839 --> 00:54:22,710
I was in Africa
for a period of six years.

961
00:54:22,710 --> 00:54:26,113
It was sort of like
the "flower power" days

962
00:54:26,113 --> 00:54:28,182
In Nigeria, you know?

963
00:54:28,182 --> 00:54:31,285
You can't imagine
the '70s in Nigeria,

964
00:54:31,285 --> 00:54:34,288
How much fun they all had.

965
00:54:34,288 --> 00:54:36,490
[Music continues]

966
00:54:41,795 --> 00:54:45,266
Fela... We used to call him
the black president,

967
00:54:45,266 --> 00:54:47,735
And he formed
the Calakuta Party.

968
00:54:47,735 --> 00:54:52,039
And we all used to sit around
a table the shape of Africa,

969
00:54:52,039 --> 00:54:54,808
And I was elected
one of the party.

970
00:54:54,808 --> 00:54:56,143
He was just cool.

971
00:54:56,143 --> 00:54:57,445
He was real cool.

972
00:54:57,445 --> 00:54:59,380
Ginger's a cool white boy.

973
00:54:59,380 --> 00:55:01,282
Meanwhile,
no one in Europe knew

974
00:55:01,282 --> 00:55:03,217
What the fuck was going on
there.

975
00:55:03,217 --> 00:55:04,418
Nobody what?

976
00:55:04,418 --> 00:55:05,819
Nobody in Europe,

977
00:55:05,819 --> 00:55:08,222
All the people you had
left behind, you know?

978
00:55:08,222 --> 00:55:10,824
What people I'd left behind?

979
00:55:12,025 --> 00:55:14,428
I think he just goes.

980
00:55:14,428 --> 00:55:16,096
That's a great thing in music.

981
00:55:16,096 --> 00:55:18,599
You don't want to be thinking
too much when you're playing.

982
00:55:18,599 --> 00:55:21,535
He who hesitates is lost.

983
00:55:21,535 --> 00:55:23,437
Just go.

984
00:55:23,437 --> 00:55:26,440
He really desperately
wanted a boy.

985
00:55:26,440 --> 00:55:29,743
And when he got a boy,
he was awful to him.

986
00:55:29,743 --> 00:55:32,413
He said some nasty things
to my mom.

987
00:55:33,447 --> 00:55:36,884
Like, "I wish I had black kids,"
or something.

988
00:55:36,884 --> 00:55:38,986
Were you guys still in contact
with him?

989
00:55:38,986 --> 00:55:40,120
Yeah, yeah.

990
00:55:40,120 --> 00:55:41,389
He would just call you?

991
00:55:41,389 --> 00:55:45,058
Yeah.
Like, "Hello. I'm in prison."

992
00:55:45,058 --> 00:55:46,460
"Fine."

993
00:55:46,460 --> 00:55:49,730
I was approached
by Range Rover.

994
00:55:49,730 --> 00:55:55,536
Would I join them in a three-car
team for this Show 1000 rally?

995
00:55:55,536 --> 00:55:58,339
Anyway, I arrived
at the checkpoint

996
00:55:58,339 --> 00:56:01,008
And did 180
and came in backwards.

997
00:56:01,008 --> 00:56:03,944
And I heard this voice say,
"Bloody hell!

998
00:56:03,944 --> 00:56:06,647
The way you drive,
you should play polo."

999
00:56:06,647 --> 00:56:08,316
And I shouted out of the window,

1000
00:56:08,316 --> 00:56:10,484
"You've got to be
bloody kidding."

1001
00:56:10,484 --> 00:56:12,886
He said,
"Okay, Baker. Come with me."

1002
00:56:12,886 --> 00:56:14,422
So off we go.

1003
00:56:14,422 --> 00:56:16,223
And where do we go?

1004
00:56:16,223 --> 00:56:18,025
Lagos Polo Club.

1005
00:56:18,025 --> 00:56:22,430
And I've already downed about
eight or nine Bacardi and Cokes,

1006
00:56:22,430 --> 00:56:25,299
And Colin comes up to me
and says, "Right, Baker."

1007
00:56:25,299 --> 00:56:27,401
It's time you got on a horse."

1008
00:56:27,401 --> 00:56:30,638
And Colin gets out a whip
and goes whack!

1009
00:56:30,638 --> 00:56:35,108
Boom! It's off
like fucking 900 miles an hour.

1010
00:56:35,108 --> 00:56:36,710
Absolutely full gallop.

1011
00:56:36,710 --> 00:56:39,680
My sunglasses were around
one side of my face,

1012
00:56:39,680 --> 00:56:43,083
And my beard's around the other,
but I was still on the horse.

1013
00:56:43,083 --> 00:56:45,986
And I said, "Where's
the fucking brakes, Colin?"

1014
00:56:45,986 --> 00:56:47,888
[Laughs]

1015
00:56:47,888 --> 00:56:50,991
So I'd found
an old pair of boots

1016
00:56:50,991 --> 00:56:55,996
And an old polo stick and a hat,
and I became a poloist.

1017
00:56:55,996 --> 00:56:57,798
[Laughs]

1018
00:56:57,798 --> 00:56:59,199
[Drums playing]

1019
00:56:59,199 --> 00:57:00,568
The class of Nigerians

1020
00:57:00,568 --> 00:57:04,204
That would have belonged
to the Lagos Polo Club

1021
00:57:04,204 --> 00:57:05,973
Were very elite people,

1022
00:57:05,973 --> 00:57:08,509
People that Fela would dismiss
as having a so-called

1023
00:57:08,509 --> 00:57:10,077
"Colonial mentality."

1024
00:57:10,077 --> 00:57:11,812
Those were definitely the people

1025
00:57:11,812 --> 00:57:15,248
That Fela was singing against
in the 1970s.

1026
00:57:15,248 --> 00:57:16,517
But it was later in the '70s

1027
00:57:16,517 --> 00:57:18,218
When Fela really got
more radicalized

1028
00:57:18,218 --> 00:57:20,754
And began to live the life
of a musical dissident.

1029
00:57:20,754 --> 00:57:23,190
All this nonsense
hanging around here.

1030
00:57:23,190 --> 00:57:24,558
They sit there in cars, man!

1031
00:57:24,558 --> 00:57:28,328
Fela took on
the government, the army.

1032
00:57:28,328 --> 00:57:32,400
He was determined
to become president.

1033
00:57:32,400 --> 00:57:36,637
All the government top guys
played polo,

1034
00:57:36,637 --> 00:57:39,840
So they were always
at the Lagos Polo Club.

1035
00:57:39,840 --> 00:57:42,009
So I was playing polo there

1036
00:57:42,009 --> 00:57:46,046
And hanging out with,
as it were, Fela's enemies.

1037
00:57:46,046 --> 00:57:49,717
And a lot of the people
on Fela's committee

1038
00:57:49,717 --> 00:57:56,557
Didn't like that and soured
Fela's mind against me.

1039
00:57:56,557 --> 00:57:58,959
I was pretty upset at the time.

1040
00:57:58,959 --> 00:58:00,327
About what?

1041
00:58:00,327 --> 00:58:06,734
Well, that Fela wouldn't play
with me, with his band.

1042
00:58:06,734 --> 00:58:09,870
On Friday, February 18, 1977,

1043
00:58:09,870 --> 00:58:12,473
A thousand-odd soldiers
surround Calakuta,

1044
00:58:12,473 --> 00:58:14,074
Machine guns at the ready.

1045
00:58:14,074 --> 00:58:15,375
They plunder the house.

1046
00:58:15,375 --> 00:58:18,345
Their clubs spare neither
pregnant women nor children.

1047
00:58:18,345 --> 00:58:20,614
Fela himself
is seriously beaten.

1048
00:58:20,614 --> 00:58:23,417
Fela and his tribe
find themselves in prison.

1049
00:58:23,417 --> 00:58:25,553
It was starting to go wrong,
yeah.

1050
00:58:25,553 --> 00:58:28,622
But, I mean, I left Nigeria

1051
00:58:28,622 --> 00:58:31,459
Because I lost my studio,
really.

1052
00:58:31,459 --> 00:58:33,727
It took us three years
to build it.

1053
00:58:33,727 --> 00:58:36,363
It's been open
just over two years now.

1054
00:58:36,363 --> 00:58:37,965
It's coming along great.

1055
00:58:46,273 --> 00:58:48,642
Presumably, there must be
a lot of music there.

1056
00:58:48,642 --> 00:58:50,778
Yeah.
We kept pretty busy.

1057
00:58:50,778 --> 00:58:53,113
We were working
all the time, yeah.

1058
00:58:53,113 --> 00:58:56,584
I think as a businessperson,
he's a walking disaster area.

1059
00:58:56,584 --> 00:59:01,254
Ginger's out there, discovering
a whole new world of sound...

1060
00:59:01,254 --> 00:59:03,056
Literally a whole new world
of sound...

1061
00:59:03,056 --> 00:59:07,728
And recording it in good faith,
not even blind faith.

1062
00:59:07,728 --> 00:59:09,497
Along comes
a gangster record company

1063
00:59:09,497 --> 00:59:11,431
And says, "We can take advantage
of that."

1064
00:59:11,431 --> 00:59:13,133
And Ginger was just taken
for a ride.

1065
00:59:13,133 --> 00:59:15,536
He said,
"You can't build a studio here.

1066
00:59:15,536 --> 00:59:17,404
This is our territory."

1067
00:59:17,404 --> 00:59:20,808
They banned all the artists
they had under contract

1068
00:59:20,808 --> 00:59:24,344
From using my studio.

1069
00:59:24,344 --> 00:59:26,647
I told him to fuck off.

1070
00:59:30,417 --> 00:59:31,819
So shortly after that,

1071
00:59:31,819 --> 00:59:34,955
Three armed soldiers entered
the studio.

1072
00:59:34,955 --> 00:59:37,925
So I just leapt out of the room,
over the balcony,

1073
00:59:37,925 --> 00:59:44,031
Got in the Range Rover, and went
straight towards the road.

1074
00:59:44,031 --> 00:59:45,398
[Gunshots]

1075
00:59:45,398 --> 00:59:48,468
I could hear all these gunshots
and ricochets going on

1076
00:59:48,468 --> 00:59:51,104
Where the police
are trying to shoot me.

1077
00:59:51,104 --> 00:59:53,541
Why did Ginger leave?

1078
00:59:53,541 --> 00:59:55,643
I just know
things were not going right.

1079
00:59:55,643 --> 01:00:00,180
But when he left,
Fela and him lost contact.

1080
01:00:37,084 --> 01:00:40,487
You had been off the scene
in Africa for so many years.

1081
01:00:40,487 --> 01:00:44,091
You must have missed being
a rock star to a certain extent.

1082
01:00:44,091 --> 01:00:46,026
No, I didn't.

1083
01:00:47,027 --> 01:00:51,832
I came back to England to play
with the Gurvitz brothers,

1084
01:00:51,832 --> 01:00:54,234
For which I got some money.

1085
01:00:54,234 --> 01:00:59,406
I'd just lost a fortune, so it
was a matter of doing some work.

1086
01:01:00,140 --> 01:01:03,310
That was really
all he could get, wasn't it?

1087
01:01:03,310 --> 01:01:05,913
At that time,
nobody wanted to work with him.

1088
01:01:07,347 --> 01:01:09,416
* Now is the time *

1089
01:01:09,416 --> 01:01:11,451
* Get it all together *

1090
01:01:11,451 --> 01:01:14,287
Shut up, you bloody fool!

1091
01:01:14,287 --> 01:01:15,555
* Now is the time *

1092
01:01:15,555 --> 01:01:18,391
- Hey!
- * Put yourself together *

1093
01:01:18,391 --> 01:01:23,897
Yeah, I grew up in the downward
spiral of his life,

1094
01:01:23,897 --> 01:01:26,266
Everything collapsing
and falling apart.

1095
01:01:26,266 --> 01:01:30,838
The mistake I made
was letting polo take over

1096
01:01:30,838 --> 01:01:33,206
From thinking about work.

1097
01:01:33,206 --> 01:01:37,010
The tax people saw this film
the BBC did

1098
01:01:37,010 --> 01:01:41,014
Of these horses arriving
and gave the impression

1099
01:01:41,014 --> 01:01:43,283
That I'd got a hell of a lot
of money.

1100
01:01:43,283 --> 01:01:48,088
Only this week, 30 polo ponies
arrived from Argentina.

1101
01:01:48,088 --> 01:01:51,491
This air shipment guarantees
Ginger Baker's commitment

1102
01:01:51,491 --> 01:01:55,228
To a sport that stands for
everything he isn't.

1103
01:01:55,228 --> 01:01:58,065
I went absolutely broke.

1104
01:01:58,065 --> 01:02:03,103
It was a very bad time
altogether.

1105
01:02:03,103 --> 01:02:08,475
He left my mom for my first
boyfriend's sister.

1106
01:02:08,976 --> 01:02:13,280
That was his second wife,
was my first boyfriend's sister.

1107
01:02:13,280 --> 01:02:16,483
There's a good idea!

1108
01:02:16,483 --> 01:02:18,118
She was 18, you know?

1109
01:02:18,118 --> 01:02:20,120
[Laughs]

1110
01:02:20,120 --> 01:02:23,023
Well, maybe 17.
I don't know.

1111
01:02:23,023 --> 01:02:25,592
She was still going to school.

1112
01:02:26,326 --> 01:02:29,863
She was a very naughty-type
girl, yeah.

1113
01:02:31,699 --> 01:02:35,468
Very sexy-type girl.

1114
01:02:35,468 --> 01:02:37,805
* Powder blues *

1115
01:02:42,375 --> 01:02:46,814
The tax people go, "You owe us,
you know, £150,000."

1116
01:02:46,814 --> 01:02:49,382
And it's like, you know,
he doesn't have £150,000,

1117
01:02:49,382 --> 01:02:51,118
So they took the house.

1118
01:02:51,118 --> 01:02:52,986
We'd lived in that house
all our lives.

1119
01:02:52,986 --> 01:02:54,554
And then one day you come home

1120
01:02:54,554 --> 01:02:56,123
And there's a whole load
of police

1121
01:02:56,123 --> 01:02:57,624
And a whole load of bailiffs,

1122
01:02:57,624 --> 01:02:59,626
And they just won't let you
back into your house.

1123
01:02:59,626 --> 01:03:02,162
And they just take everything
that you've ever owned.

1124
01:03:02,162 --> 01:03:04,031
I just, you know, took my drums

1125
01:03:04,031 --> 01:03:07,034
And went and lived
on the streets, lived in squats.

1126
01:03:07,034 --> 01:03:09,502
You know, I used to
tie my drums to my hands

1127
01:03:09,502 --> 01:03:13,306
When I went to sleep
so that no one could take them.

1128
01:03:13,306 --> 01:03:15,642
You know, I don't think
he should've had a family.

1129
01:03:15,642 --> 01:03:18,045
I think he would have been
way better off in his life

1130
01:03:18,045 --> 01:03:21,214
If he'd never had kids and just,
you know, did his thing.

1131
01:03:22,582 --> 01:03:26,153
He would have left
a lot less of a mess behind.

1132
01:03:27,420 --> 01:03:30,824
Most of the time Ginger was
with Baker Gurvitz Army,

1133
01:03:30,824 --> 01:03:33,193
He wasn't really
on the hard stuff.

1134
01:03:33,193 --> 01:03:34,261
Oh, yeah.

1135
01:03:34,261 --> 01:03:39,332
I'm a lot, you know...
better in myself.

1136
01:03:39,332 --> 01:03:41,634
Fit and well,
if you like, you know?

1137
01:03:41,634 --> 01:03:43,270
The hard stuff came back

1138
01:03:43,270 --> 01:03:46,073
In the recording
of "Hearts on Fire."

1139
01:03:46,073 --> 01:03:49,342
[Mid-tempo rock music plays]

1140
01:03:54,681 --> 01:03:59,452
It was sort of like
a pretty disastrous period,

1141
01:03:59,452 --> 01:04:01,989
So I got back into using.

1142
01:04:01,989 --> 01:04:03,757
And that's
when you sort of realize

1143
01:04:03,757 --> 01:04:08,695
Your idols have feet of clay,
the slight inkling coming in

1144
01:04:08,695 --> 01:04:11,164
That this person isn't
in control.

1145
01:04:11,164 --> 01:04:14,701
The cameraman's in control.

1146
01:04:14,701 --> 01:04:16,770
Hello.

1147
01:04:16,770 --> 01:04:18,571
Um...

1148
01:04:18,571 --> 01:04:20,473
What were you saying?

1149
01:04:20,473 --> 01:04:22,776
[Music continues]

1150
01:04:41,728 --> 01:04:44,131
[Guitar strums,
feedback rumbles]

1151
01:04:44,131 --> 01:04:46,566
Jeff, get us a glass of wine,
will you?

1152
01:04:46,566 --> 01:04:48,902
[Clattering]

1153
01:04:48,902 --> 01:04:51,571
Fucking hell, man.
I tried hard.

1154
01:04:51,571 --> 01:04:53,340
[Tape rewinds]

1155
01:04:53,340 --> 01:04:57,477
I'd decided, "I'd better
get away from anybody I know"

1156
01:04:57,477 --> 01:05:00,147
If I'm ever going to
get straight."

1157
01:05:00,147 --> 01:05:03,550
So I decided to go to Italy.

1158
01:05:03,550 --> 01:05:06,153
I went to Italy with Sarah,

1159
01:05:06,153 --> 01:05:09,890
Living on this place right
on top of a fucking mountain,

1160
01:05:09,890 --> 01:05:13,026
And I've never lived
in England since.

1161
01:05:13,026 --> 01:05:14,862
I didn't know anybody.

1162
01:05:14,862 --> 01:05:17,030
I didn't even speak Italian.

1163
01:05:17,030 --> 01:05:20,500
And the house was falling down.

1164
01:05:20,500 --> 01:05:23,536
I met him in '86,

1165
01:05:23,536 --> 01:05:27,540
And I was asked to find him by
a singer called Johnny Rotten,

1166
01:05:27,540 --> 01:05:29,309
Who was in The Sex Pistols.

1167
01:05:29,309 --> 01:05:33,713
He was living
in a pretty obscure situation,

1168
01:05:33,713 --> 01:05:35,382
Rough situation.

1169
01:05:35,382 --> 01:05:38,585
And in the house, which was
completely in kind of shambles,

1170
01:05:38,585 --> 01:05:42,990
I think there was two horses
and seven dogs, no electricity,

1171
01:05:42,990 --> 01:05:45,025
And a room that overlooked
the mountain

1172
01:05:45,025 --> 01:05:46,994
With a drum kit in it...
Only a drum kit.

1173
01:05:46,994 --> 01:05:50,430
But when he played in that room
and it echoed over the hills,

1174
01:05:50,430 --> 01:05:53,934
You could hear people
like five miles away, screaming,

1175
01:05:53,934 --> 01:05:55,702
"Ginger!
'Wheels of fire'!"

1176
01:05:55,702 --> 01:05:59,672
Sarah obviously married him
because she wanted a rock star.

1177
01:05:59,672 --> 01:06:01,108
Hey, you know?

1178
01:06:01,108 --> 01:06:03,610
And he took her
to this little bum-fuck town,

1179
01:06:03,610 --> 01:06:05,879
And she was like,
"Well, what the hell?" you know?

1180
01:06:05,879 --> 01:06:07,414
"Where's all
the rock-star shit?"

1181
01:06:07,414 --> 01:06:09,950
And when I went out there
with some young people,

1182
01:06:09,950 --> 01:06:12,319
She went off with one of them,
and that was the end of that.

1183
01:06:12,319 --> 01:06:13,887
And he was
absolutely devastated,

1184
01:06:13,887 --> 01:06:17,624
Because he couldn't handle
his own medicine, unfortunately.

1185
01:06:19,359 --> 01:06:22,029
Was he heartbroken?
Oh, yeah.

1186
01:06:22,029 --> 01:06:24,431
Yeah.
She fucked him good, yeah.

1187
01:06:24,431 --> 01:06:26,866
I was completely
fucking destroyed.

1188
01:06:26,866 --> 01:06:31,471
I was on my own with all my dogs
and a couple of horses.

1189
01:06:32,572 --> 01:06:34,774
[Chuckles]

1190
01:06:34,774 --> 01:06:38,111
I mean, it was terrible.

1191
01:06:38,111 --> 01:06:40,547
I went out there to get
drum lessons and stuff.

1192
01:06:40,547 --> 01:06:41,915
He had no money,

1193
01:06:41,915 --> 01:06:44,784
So he couldn't get me
a plane ticket back to England.

1194
01:06:44,784 --> 01:06:46,386
So we had to do this gig.

1195
01:06:46,386 --> 01:06:49,089
So I got really, really sick,
right, the day of the gig.

1196
01:06:49,089 --> 01:06:51,391
I was sitting on a chair,
and I was throwing up,

1197
01:06:51,391 --> 01:06:53,093
And I was just, like,
a really bad way.

1198
01:06:53,093 --> 01:06:55,128
I was like,
"I don't know if I can play."

1199
01:06:55,128 --> 01:06:57,998
So, you know,
he chops out a line of cocaine.

1200
01:06:57,998 --> 01:06:59,266
"Take this."

1201
01:06:59,266 --> 01:07:01,201
I'd never done cocaine before,
you know?

1202
01:07:01,201 --> 01:07:03,470
Like, "I'm 15 years old,"
you know?

1203
01:07:03,470 --> 01:07:05,705
So I ended up taking this line
of cocaine.

1204
01:07:05,705 --> 01:07:07,274
Played the gig fine.

1205
01:07:07,274 --> 01:07:10,543
Somehow, it just, like,
you know, makes you feel good.

1206
01:07:10,543 --> 01:07:14,447
So then he put me on a coach
back to England, you know,

1207
01:07:14,447 --> 01:07:16,016
And he took the rest
of the money

1208
01:07:16,016 --> 01:07:17,450
And wouldn't get me
a plane ticket.

1209
01:07:17,450 --> 01:07:19,452
And we made good money
at that gig.

1210
01:07:19,452 --> 01:07:21,521
[Dog barking]

1211
01:07:31,298 --> 01:07:36,569
I started getting these letters
from some guy in L.A.

1212
01:07:36,569 --> 01:07:38,205
He kept saying, "Oh, man",

1213
01:07:38,205 --> 01:07:41,374
You've got a fantastic career
in films."

1214
01:07:41,374 --> 01:07:43,676
[Gasps]

1215
01:07:43,676 --> 01:07:46,113
So I went to California.

1216
01:07:46,113 --> 01:07:48,481
[Drums playing]

1217
01:07:53,186 --> 01:07:56,789
"The Nasty Boys"
was the most extraordinary,

1218
01:07:56,789 --> 01:07:59,759
Stupid thing I've ever seen.

1219
01:07:59,759 --> 01:08:01,928
[Overdubbed scream]

1220
01:08:01,928 --> 01:08:03,296
"Aah!"

1221
01:08:03,296 --> 01:08:06,133
Hollywood.
Bah.

1222
01:08:06,133 --> 01:08:08,335
[Sighs]
That was the end of it for me.

1223
01:08:08,335 --> 01:08:10,303
I mean, it was just so stupid.

1224
01:08:10,303 --> 01:08:13,473
Last one on is a rotten egg.

1225
01:08:13,473 --> 01:08:15,242
I hadn't seen him for years.

1226
01:08:15,242 --> 01:08:17,644
When I arrived in L.A.,
I didn't recognize him,

1227
01:08:17,644 --> 01:08:19,712
'Cause he looked like
an old man.

1228
01:08:19,712 --> 01:08:21,414
And I thought, "Where's my dad?"

1229
01:08:21,414 --> 01:08:25,085
He actually put an ad
on Music Connection magazine

1230
01:08:25,085 --> 01:08:26,553
Looking for a job.

1231
01:08:26,553 --> 01:08:28,121
"Famous drummer from the '60s,"

1232
01:08:28,121 --> 01:08:29,689
You know,
"Ginger Baker from Cream,

1233
01:08:29,689 --> 01:08:32,159
Looking for a band
to play with."

1234
01:08:33,826 --> 01:08:35,895
Are you ready to go?

1235
01:08:35,895 --> 01:08:39,799
Okay. So this is a drum kit,
and I'm Ginger Baker.

1236
01:08:39,799 --> 01:08:42,169
You hold the drumstick thusly,

1237
01:08:42,169 --> 01:08:45,505
And you play the stick
like that.

1238
01:08:45,505 --> 01:08:48,241
The 1960s were heady times
for Ginger Baker.

1239
01:08:48,241 --> 01:08:49,576
He was a drummer

1240
01:08:49,576 --> 01:08:51,544
For some of rock music's
most influential groups.

1241
01:08:51,544 --> 01:08:53,413
We visited Baker
at the ranch he rents

1242
01:08:53,413 --> 01:08:56,516
In the California desert
as he tries to come back.

1243
01:08:56,516 --> 01:08:59,186
Tell me about your relationship
these days with Eric Clapton.

1244
01:08:59,186 --> 01:09:00,687
Do you still speak?

1245
01:09:00,687 --> 01:09:04,491
I don't have a lot in common
with Eric nowadays.

1246
01:09:06,326 --> 01:09:09,262
He's sort of...

1247
01:09:10,397 --> 01:09:12,832
Changed considerably.

1248
01:09:12,832 --> 01:09:14,201
Ginger, the way he is

1249
01:09:14,201 --> 01:09:16,769
And the way, you know,
his self-medication

1250
01:09:16,769 --> 01:09:19,606
And all of the kind of things
that go on in his life,

1251
01:09:19,606 --> 01:09:23,443
I would find quite hard to be
around for any length of time.

1252
01:09:23,443 --> 01:09:25,945
It was quite threatening,
you know, to me

1253
01:09:25,945 --> 01:09:28,748
And I suppose what I would call
my sobriety.

1254
01:09:28,748 --> 01:09:31,318
But I've always
got time for him, you know,

1255
01:09:31,318 --> 01:09:33,120
And I know he knows that.

1256
01:09:33,120 --> 01:09:36,489
There was nothing starlike
about him when I first met him.

1257
01:09:36,489 --> 01:09:38,625
He was pretty much penniless
when we met

1258
01:09:38,625 --> 01:09:42,829
And had spent everything to get
his horses over to America.

1259
01:09:42,829 --> 01:09:44,164
I was pretty happy.

1260
01:09:44,164 --> 01:09:45,932
I was gonna be going into
a master's program

1261
01:09:45,932 --> 01:09:47,534
And following medicine.

1262
01:09:47,534 --> 01:09:49,536
There was a lot of great stuff
ahead of me.

1263
01:09:49,536 --> 01:09:52,705
And then I got
a little derailed.

1264
01:09:52,705 --> 01:09:54,407
Was Karen a good person?

1265
01:09:57,377 --> 01:10:00,447
I don't want to discuss Karen.

1266
01:10:00,447 --> 01:10:04,317
He is somebody
who needs to be cared for,

1267
01:10:04,317 --> 01:10:06,686
And maybe that's what was
so attractive to me.

1268
01:10:06,686 --> 01:10:08,521
It was like,
"I can help this person."

1269
01:10:08,521 --> 01:10:10,823
He was somebody really
interesting to spend time with.

1270
01:10:10,823 --> 01:10:12,792
He started playing the drums,
and actually,

1271
01:10:12,792 --> 01:10:16,329
That was the first time
I really understood the drums.

1272
01:10:22,602 --> 01:10:24,571
Nobody wanted to play with him.

1273
01:10:24,571 --> 01:10:25,872
And this is L.A.

1274
01:10:25,872 --> 01:10:29,008
I mean, there should have been
gigs everywhere for him.

1275
01:10:29,008 --> 01:10:32,612
People were just like, "Mm. No.
It's too much trouble."

1276
01:10:34,547 --> 01:10:38,017
And then finally, he did join
The Masters of Reality.

1277
01:10:38,017 --> 01:10:40,753
* John Brown, bring him down *

1278
01:10:40,753 --> 01:10:44,191
* Pull his body to the ground *

1279
01:10:44,191 --> 01:10:46,626
[Mid-tempo rock music plays]

1280
01:10:48,661 --> 01:10:51,764
It was really
quite an enjoyable thing,

1281
01:10:51,764 --> 01:10:54,000
That Masters of Reality.

1282
01:10:54,000 --> 01:10:57,937
They were trying to say it was
heavy metal, which it wasn't.

1283
01:10:57,937 --> 01:11:02,842
It was music
you couldn't put in a box, Jay.

1284
01:11:07,247 --> 01:11:09,749
"Sunrise on the Sufferbus."

1285
01:11:09,749 --> 01:11:12,485
Musician magazine
simply calls "Sufferbus"

1286
01:11:12,485 --> 01:11:14,987
"The best rock album
of the young decade."

1287
01:11:14,987 --> 01:11:17,924
When we were on tour
with Alice In Chains,

1288
01:11:17,924 --> 01:11:19,392
I think it was a mismatch.

1289
01:11:19,392 --> 01:11:21,361
Most of the crowd to begin with

1290
01:11:21,361 --> 01:11:23,830
Didn't know
who Ginger Baker was.

1291
01:11:23,830 --> 01:11:27,033
Kids in the front row
with Megadeth T-shirts on

1292
01:11:27,033 --> 01:11:29,202
Throwing stuff at Ginger.

1293
01:11:29,202 --> 01:11:31,704
How much can a man take?

1294
01:11:31,704 --> 01:11:33,806
He was having to start
all over again,

1295
01:11:33,806 --> 01:11:35,242
Just like a new musician.

1296
01:11:35,242 --> 01:11:38,144
And they were treating him like,
"You know, you should be happy.

1297
01:11:38,144 --> 01:11:39,512
"We got you a tour bus.

1298
01:11:39,512 --> 01:11:41,113
A lot of musicians don't have
tour buses."

1299
01:11:41,113 --> 01:11:45,117
And he's like, "I did this,
you know, 30 years ago."

1300
01:11:45,117 --> 01:11:46,486
I don't want to do this again."

1301
01:11:46,486 --> 01:11:49,622
Do you think Nirvana
is the new Cream?

1302
01:11:50,723 --> 01:11:54,827
He had gotten a taste
of American music business,

1303
01:11:54,827 --> 01:11:58,631
Class of '93,
and he spit it out.

1304
01:11:58,631 --> 01:12:01,234
And I don't fucking blame him
one bit.

1305
01:12:01,234 --> 01:12:04,471
I didn't like L.A. at all.

1306
01:12:04,471 --> 01:12:07,206
He wasn't getting along
with the whole polo community

1307
01:12:07,206 --> 01:12:08,775
In California at that time,

1308
01:12:08,775 --> 01:12:12,044
So he was just ready to move on
and start all over again.

1309
01:12:12,044 --> 01:12:14,581
[Music continues]

1310
01:12:14,581 --> 01:12:17,250
When he left
to come out here to Colorado,

1311
01:12:17,250 --> 01:12:19,018
Nobody wanted to play with him
anymore.

1312
01:12:19,018 --> 01:12:22,322
So we started a polo club
called Mile High Polo.

1313
01:12:22,322 --> 01:12:23,923
And that worked out beautifully,

1314
01:12:23,923 --> 01:12:26,225
Because he didn't have to go
and play with other people.

1315
01:12:26,225 --> 01:12:27,527
They had to come play with him.

1316
01:12:27,527 --> 01:12:29,662
Here comes Ginger Baker.

1317
01:12:29,662 --> 01:12:30,963
Not only can he play drums,

1318
01:12:30,963 --> 01:12:33,065
But he can hit that ball
down the field.

1319
01:12:33,065 --> 01:12:35,802
People would come out, bring
their kids, bring their dogs.

1320
01:12:35,802 --> 01:12:38,338
We'd have polo
and then jazz in the park.

1321
01:12:38,338 --> 01:12:42,174
He would get off the horse,
come over in his polo uniform,

1322
01:12:42,174 --> 01:12:43,676
And sit down at the drums.

1323
01:12:43,676 --> 01:12:45,912
And then we'd just go
into something from there.

1324
01:12:45,912 --> 01:12:48,180
So it was a pretty wild
experience to see.

1325
01:12:48,180 --> 01:12:50,483
And you could feel
the passion of both things.

1326
01:12:50,483 --> 01:12:52,785
[Up-tempo jazz playing]

1327
01:12:57,390 --> 01:13:03,696
DJQ20... It was probably
the best band I had.

1328
01:13:03,696 --> 01:13:10,570
It was great playing jazz,
again... the music I came from.

1329
01:13:10,570 --> 01:13:12,772
[Music continues]

1330
01:13:14,006 --> 01:13:16,576
Kofi was living with us
at the time,

1331
01:13:16,576 --> 01:13:19,912
And we used to do
a lot of drum things together.

1332
01:13:26,786 --> 01:13:28,688
He's got a prodigious technique.

1333
01:13:28,688 --> 01:13:31,123
He's got the most amazing
technique.

1334
01:13:31,123 --> 01:13:33,059
He's a hell of a sweet kid.

1335
01:13:33,059 --> 01:13:35,995
It was the closest
I ever got to my dad.

1336
01:13:35,995 --> 01:13:37,964
It was great fun.

1337
01:13:38,865 --> 01:13:41,000
And I actually got to play
with my dad,

1338
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:43,936
And there was some form
of bond going on.

1339
01:13:43,936 --> 01:13:46,439
I mean, I wish I could have
done that my whole life.

1340
01:13:46,439 --> 01:13:48,408
It would've been great.

1341
01:14:05,358 --> 01:14:08,928
He comes out of jazz,
plays rock, plays world music.

1342
01:14:08,928 --> 01:14:11,698
I just thought, "We should
get some music together"

1343
01:14:11,698 --> 01:14:13,900
"That shows him
as this major cat,

1344
01:14:13,900 --> 01:14:16,836
"Not, you know,
a lesser light than Max Roach,

1345
01:14:16,836 --> 01:14:18,771
But his own personal music."

1346
01:14:18,771 --> 01:14:23,075
Ron so inspired Ginger,
Ginger began to practice.

1347
01:14:23,075 --> 01:14:24,911
He began to rehearse.

1348
01:14:24,911 --> 01:14:26,713
Then, finally,
they came to New York

1349
01:14:26,713 --> 01:14:28,615
And played a gig at the Iridium

1350
01:14:28,615 --> 01:14:31,818
And just blew the doors
off the place.

1351
01:14:31,818 --> 01:14:34,120
It went down
like a fucking bomb.

1352
01:14:34,120 --> 01:14:36,689
[Up-tempo jazz playing]

1353
01:14:42,061 --> 01:14:45,698
At the Iridium in New York,
Max Roach came to the gig.

1354
01:14:45,698 --> 01:14:49,001
The first record he ever bought
was Max Roach.

1355
01:14:49,001 --> 01:14:51,538
I did one of the best solos
I've ever done

1356
01:14:51,538 --> 01:14:53,673
When Max was there.

1357
01:15:04,283 --> 01:15:07,219
[Cheers and applause]

1358
01:15:07,219 --> 01:15:09,556
I could see Ginger's face
on the break.

1359
01:15:09,556 --> 01:15:11,057
Max hugged him.

1360
01:15:11,057 --> 01:15:13,960
It was like Max was saying,
"Yeah. You're in here.

1361
01:15:13,960 --> 01:15:15,227
You're one of us."

1362
01:15:15,227 --> 01:15:18,898
He just had tears
coming down his face,

1363
01:15:18,898 --> 01:15:22,769
Because he had achieved
the pinnacle of jazz

1364
01:15:22,769 --> 01:15:25,605
For an improvising musician
and a drummer.

1365
01:15:25,605 --> 01:15:28,675
He has a working band
that can go toe-to-toe

1366
01:15:28,675 --> 01:15:32,078
With any band in New York,
let alone planet Earth.

1367
01:15:32,078 --> 01:15:34,647
And he had not only
been accepted,

1368
01:15:34,647 --> 01:15:38,317
But accepted as a peer
and an equal.

1369
01:15:38,317 --> 01:15:41,087
The actual words Max said were,

1370
01:15:41,087 --> 01:15:45,057
"Jesus,
Ginger plays like a nigger."

1371
01:15:45,057 --> 01:15:46,593
[Chuckles]

1372
01:15:46,593 --> 01:15:49,462
That, coming from someone
like Max Roach,

1373
01:15:49,462 --> 01:15:55,334
Was an enormous compliment,
you know?

1374
01:15:56,235 --> 01:16:00,306
Four drummers in my life
that were absolute heroes.

1375
01:16:00,306 --> 01:16:02,775
Phil Seamen was the first one,

1376
01:16:02,775 --> 01:16:07,346
Max Roach, Art Blakey,
and Elvin Jones.

1377
01:16:07,346 --> 01:16:11,117
All four of them
became friends...

1378
01:16:11,117 --> 01:16:13,720
I mean friends.

1379
01:16:13,720 --> 01:16:15,221
Dear friends.

1380
01:16:15,221 --> 01:16:19,759
[Voice breaking]
And that to me is worth...

1381
01:16:19,759 --> 01:16:22,962
More to me
than anything in the world.

1382
01:16:22,962 --> 01:16:25,965
[Down-tempo jazz playing]

1383
01:16:44,917 --> 01:16:49,055
Anywhere Ginger goes,
it's just a matter of time

1384
01:16:49,055 --> 01:16:52,258
Before there's gonna be
controversy going on.

1385
01:16:53,225 --> 01:16:56,062
Somebody did a very nasty

1386
01:16:56,062 --> 01:17:00,432
And resulted in Liz
getting arrested yesterday

1387
01:17:00,432 --> 01:17:03,135
By the immigration people.

1388
01:17:03,135 --> 01:17:05,572
He had an English groom
that was living with us.

1389
01:17:05,572 --> 01:17:08,841
But because her immigration
papers hadn't come through yet,

1390
01:17:08,841 --> 01:17:11,477
She was illegal,
and so they took her away.

1391
01:17:11,477 --> 01:17:14,280
And I started going crazy.

1392
01:17:14,280 --> 01:17:18,017
And there was these two guys,
Louis & Floorwax,

1393
01:17:18,017 --> 01:17:20,920
Who had a radio show
that I was on.

1394
01:17:20,920 --> 01:17:23,355
He came on the radio show
one morning

1395
01:17:23,355 --> 01:17:24,891
And started talking about it.

1396
01:17:24,891 --> 01:17:27,560
And he literally told everybody
to fuck off.

1397
01:17:27,560 --> 01:17:29,996
I mean, this is a foul deed.

1398
01:17:29,996 --> 01:17:32,765
He said something about
the United States of America

1399
01:17:32,765 --> 01:17:35,501
Can kiss my ass or blow me
or something like that.

1400
01:17:35,501 --> 01:17:37,904
I think that's the last thing
he said on our show.

1401
01:17:37,904 --> 01:17:39,806
I believe that was
the final sentence.

1402
01:17:39,806 --> 01:17:41,608
So we ended the interview,

1403
01:17:41,608 --> 01:17:44,076
And next thing we heard,
he was deported.

1404
01:17:44,076 --> 01:17:46,879
He thought he was seeing
the writing on the wall.

1405
01:17:46,879 --> 01:17:48,781
I'm the next target now.

1406
01:17:48,781 --> 01:17:50,817
So he decided to grab his toys
and leave

1407
01:17:50,817 --> 01:17:53,085
Before they could kick him out.

1408
01:17:53,085 --> 01:17:56,122
People are saying it's one of
the best records he's ever done,

1409
01:17:56,122 --> 01:17:57,356
And then he left.

1410
01:17:57,356 --> 01:18:00,593
We just put this record out,
and he just split.

1411
01:18:00,593 --> 01:18:02,528
Kofi would come over
every single day

1412
01:18:02,528 --> 01:18:03,830
And play with his dad.

1413
01:18:03,830 --> 01:18:05,732
And then a couple days
before he left,

1414
01:18:05,732 --> 01:18:08,000
Kind of like you
with the cane to your face,

1415
01:18:08,000 --> 01:18:10,202
Ginger gave a verbal cane
to Kofi's face

1416
01:18:10,202 --> 01:18:12,071
And just basically I think
told him,

1417
01:18:12,071 --> 01:18:13,940
"You're a piece-of-shit drummer,

1418
01:18:13,940 --> 01:18:16,242
And you'll never be what I am,
and you just can't get it."

1419
01:18:16,242 --> 01:18:21,480
And that was it...
His way of saying goodbye.

1420
01:18:21,480 --> 01:18:23,149
Well, I asked him.

1421
01:18:23,149 --> 01:18:26,085
I said, "Do you even care about
anything I do or anything?"

1422
01:18:26,085 --> 01:18:28,020
He said, "No."
So I said, "Fine."

1423
01:18:28,020 --> 01:18:29,221
So I got in my car and left.

1424
01:18:29,221 --> 01:18:31,223
That was the last time
I saw him.

1425
01:18:31,223 --> 01:18:35,261
["Can't Find My Way Home"
plays]

1426
01:18:39,866 --> 01:18:42,769
I don't know
if it's his ability to move on

1427
01:18:42,769 --> 01:18:45,104
Or his inability to stay.

1428
01:18:45,104 --> 01:18:50,109
I think he has trouble staying,
and so moving on is his option.

1429
01:18:50,109 --> 01:18:52,011
I went with him
on several of those moves,

1430
01:18:52,011 --> 01:18:53,780
And then the last one,
I decided, "No."

1431
01:18:53,780 --> 01:18:56,649
I'm not up
for one more of these."

1432
01:18:56,649 --> 01:18:59,719
[Indistinct talking on P.A.]

1433
01:19:00,920 --> 01:19:04,691
Maybe it goes back
to when his dad died.

1434
01:19:04,691 --> 01:19:07,894
He was just kind of taken away
abruptly,

1435
01:19:07,894 --> 01:19:10,162
And there was nothing
he could do about it.

1436
01:19:11,030 --> 01:19:16,268
The only time I remember
my dad clearly is on the train,

1437
01:19:16,268 --> 01:19:19,806
When he went off
after his last leave.

1438
01:19:21,941 --> 01:19:25,812
And as the train pulled off,
I broke away from my mom

1439
01:19:25,812 --> 01:19:27,814
And went running
down the platform

1440
01:19:27,814 --> 01:19:30,817
After the train, crying.

1441
01:19:32,484 --> 01:19:37,423
It was like I knew
he wasn't coming back.

1442
01:19:37,423 --> 01:19:40,026
[Music continues]

1443
01:19:40,026 --> 01:19:45,164
* Ooh, ooh, ooh, ooh, ooh *

1444
01:19:45,164 --> 01:19:50,837
* But I can't find my way home *

1445
01:19:50,837 --> 01:19:54,540
* Can't, ooh, ooh, ooh *

1446
01:19:54,540 --> 01:19:55,842
* Ooh, ooh, ooh *

1447
01:19:55,842 --> 01:20:01,113
* But I can't find my way home *

1448
01:20:01,113 --> 01:20:06,418
* Still I can't find
my way home *

1449
01:20:06,418 --> 01:20:12,024
* And I ain't done
nothing wrong *

1450
01:20:12,024 --> 01:20:14,393
* But I can't find my way home *

1451
01:20:14,393 --> 01:20:17,696
20 years ago,
South Africa was the last place

1452
01:20:17,696 --> 01:20:19,665
I would ever have dreamt
of going,

1453
01:20:19,665 --> 01:20:21,934
Because I was so, you know,
appalled

1454
01:20:21,934 --> 01:20:24,737
At the apartheid regime.

1455
01:20:24,737 --> 01:20:26,939
Well, now it's broken up.

1456
01:20:26,939 --> 01:20:29,175
South Africa has joined
the rest of the world.

1457
01:20:29,175 --> 01:20:31,878
What are you gonna do musically
when you get there?

1458
01:20:31,878 --> 01:20:33,412
Do you have plans?

1459
01:20:33,412 --> 01:20:36,415
I have more plans
than you can dream of.

1460
01:20:36,415 --> 01:20:41,420
I mean, South Africa
is very rich musically.

1461
01:20:41,420 --> 01:20:42,955
Sweethearts
have done it all.

1462
01:20:42,955 --> 01:20:45,457
Fast broads, pretty, ambitious,

1463
01:20:45,457 --> 01:20:47,927
And after all the money
they can get out of a guy.

1464
01:20:47,927 --> 01:20:52,031
Those deadly dames leave behind
a trail of dead husbands.

1465
01:20:52,031 --> 01:20:54,166
If she has to kill somebody,
she's going to.

1466
01:20:54,166 --> 01:20:56,836
Real-life femme fatales.

1467
01:20:56,836 --> 01:21:03,242
I've got some really cool music
in my head.

1468
01:21:03,242 --> 01:21:07,379
I tried to do
the polo and jazz thing here.

1469
01:21:08,147 --> 01:21:13,185
But there's not that many
musicians over here.

1470
01:21:13,185 --> 01:21:15,254
But how much of it
is about you playing

1471
01:21:15,254 --> 01:21:17,790
Because it's
what you love doing?

1472
01:21:17,790 --> 01:21:19,325
Well, it depends.

1473
01:21:19,325 --> 01:21:23,963
To have a good time, it depends
who you're playing with.

1474
01:21:25,064 --> 01:21:27,033
I mean, five years ago,

1475
01:21:27,033 --> 01:21:30,970
The Royal Albert Hall gigs
were just fantastic.

1476
01:21:30,970 --> 01:21:33,072
[Applause]

1477
01:21:33,072 --> 01:21:36,876
[Introduction to
"We're Going Wrong" plays]

1478
01:21:48,187 --> 01:21:51,257
They were just great.

1479
01:21:51,257 --> 01:21:53,893
It was great to play with Eric,

1480
01:21:53,893 --> 01:21:56,028
And it was great to play
with Jack.

1481
01:21:56,028 --> 01:21:58,965
He did the reunion in 2005
with Cream,

1482
01:21:58,965 --> 01:22:00,332
Got a whole bunch of money,

1483
01:22:00,332 --> 01:22:05,804
And he got 24 horses
he imported from the U.K.

1484
01:22:05,804 --> 01:22:09,041
Yeah.
They cost him a fortune.

1485
01:22:09,041 --> 01:22:11,543
I've got 38 horses.

1486
01:22:12,444 --> 01:22:18,050
Horses don't let you down,
nor do dogs.

1487
01:22:18,050 --> 01:22:21,253
They all know who I am.

